  <span id="freeText13379065411573839943" style="display:none">Third time, first in over 10 years. I cannot believe that I rated this a "mere" 4 stars before (it was probably the fault of Ludvik's (Kundera's?) loathed age of callow youth, the age of the self puzzled by and obsessed with itself, the age of [<i>pace</i> Kundera] "lyrical" poetry). <br /><br />This is indeed a masterpiece—of nuance and restraint, of deliberation and yet also, at times, of abandon—and, dare I say it?—of (perhaps) mediated confession. Kundera writes elsewhere (in<i> ULB</i>) that his characters are all his own unrealized potentialities, people who have journeyed across various border-lines that he himself has not); so, if this is a <i> psychomachia</i>, then in Kundera we have a fervent Communist who has forsaken (because it has forsaken him, forsaken us) communism, a believer who has forsaken God, and an artist of all that has been forsaken by humankind, by history, who sees what is beautiful in what is forsaken <i>because</i> it has been forsaken. Our forsaking it, surely, is what has rendered it beautiful—the locus of its beauty lies in its departure from our world, in its passage into the land of all that has been forgotten and abandoned, that land which shall one day claim us, too, and all that we have ever held dear or called our own....<br /><br />Otherwise, I'm not even going to try to "review" this mysterious, captivating book just now <br />(but: <i>such</i> melancholy! What existential <i>longing</i>!<br />—punctuated, of course, by a whole other range of conflicting emotions—like life itself!)<br /><br />Is it <i>The Unbearable Lightness of Being</i>'s forerunner and postscript all in one, minus the philosophy but with an even greater attention to the beauty of the ephemeral (to the mortal, the sub-lunary, to all that is born &amp; dies in some neglected corner somewhere), if that is at all possible...?<br /><br />...Whatever it is, this book is just <u>perfect</u>.<br /> <br />&amp; It is not yet through with me.... (to be cont'd)</span>
