  <span id="freeText9619680996405042044" style="display:none">I was reading other reviews of the book on goodreads. There is one from 13 years ago (2008) and I had the exact same feeling (more/ less) while reading the book now in 2021 in my place!<br /><br />The Joke turned out to be a <i>Pandora's Box</i>. The novel dropped its curtain in an evening like this. I'm not willing to write my actual thoughts. Instead, I will offer a pseudo review. <br /><br /><i>"I started to cry which started the whole world laughing<br />Oh if I'd only seen that the joke was on me"</i> - <b>The Bee Gees</b><br /><br />Maybe that's how things turned out in the end. The bad joke which, not content with itself, had gone on multiplying itself into more and more silly jokes - finally came to a halt with nothing left to burn! The characters had long lived in bubbles that somehow managed to remain unpricked and isolated them all the more!<br /><br />As Ludvik said in the beginning, <i>"I was living in a pause."</i> Living in a pause is the worst possible feeling ever! ~ Anything that extends beyond due date may posit itself as an irony! This irony is miserable, wretched, desperate, and futile! The worst part is it was all in vain, for nothing, with nothing accomplished, and was supposed to sink into oblivion _ soon..! <br /><br />However, if you ever get to reach the bank of Morava, lie down there on the grass looking up at the sky - I wish and pray that your troubled soul may find its center of stability, rest, and peace!</span>
