<span id="freeTextContainer2150064694820518409">In &quot;The Joke&quot; we have vintage Kundera - emotionally and intellectually challenging, ripe with the intertwining symbolism of the banal and the mystical, filled to the brim with romance, tragedy, comedy, and a pastiche of kitsch, which never once falls into kitsch itself. Invoking a bit of irony, the novel is quite simply &quot;marvelous.&quot;<br/><br/>&quot;The Joke&quot; tells the story of several characters at various points in a more-or-less fifteen year period, but is principally the tale of Ludvik Jahn, a fallen Czech C</span>
  <span id="freeText2150064694820518409" style="display:none">In "The Joke" we have vintage Kundera - emotionally and intellectually challenging, ripe with the intertwining symbolism of the banal and the mystical, filled to the brim with romance, tragedy, comedy, and a pastiche of kitsch, which never once falls into kitsch itself. Invoking a bit of irony, the novel is quite simply "marvelous."<br /><br />"The Joke" tells the story of several characters at various points in a more-or-less fifteen year period, but is principally the tale of Ludvik Jahn, a fallen Czech Communist whose attempts at both sentimentality and cynicism are both crashing failures, principally due to his inability to see anything in others beyond his use for them. While Ludvig himself condemns himself for this flaw, it is revealed as a greater flaw of humanity; even those who see more of the people around them and are less selfish ultimately realize that they neither know themselves nor the objects of their affections; their desires for happiness are underlined by vague imperatives which are shaken and ultimately cast aside by the realities of the people around them.<br /><br />Stylistically, those who have read Kundera's masterpiece "The Unbearable Lightness of Being" will likely find "The Joke" a more accessible read. That said, those unfamiliar with Kundera at all will likely be thrown by his highly non-linear style. Kundera uses first-person narration throughout the story, often switching narrators with no clear identification up front as to who is speaking. While these narrations proceed in a mostly straightforward fashion in terms of chronology, the heavy emphasis on reminiscence and the prevalence of retelling of memories makes the book feel extremely non-linear. This will likely sour many readers; I can only say that your perseverance will be rewarded if you tough out the first couple of perspective/time shifts.<br /><br />In terms of pure diction, we see in "The Joke" a much more lyrically playful Kundera; the novel's text is rife with poetry and even includes musical notation in one section. Aside from these overt examples, though, the actual narration itself has a very lyrical flavor. Ludvig is as classically Eastern European as there is in fiction; everything from his advanced vocabulary to his predilection for advancing from aloof to an emotional geyser at the drop of a hat is classically European, with (deeply ironic) shades of the Russian masters Nabokov and Dostoevsky. His extreme counterpoint, Helena, is given long statements punctuated by commas, revealing a rambling mentality which never quite comes to completion. Each character has a relatively unique voice, and it is really only when a new narrator takes the stage that confusion occurs.<br /><br />The novel takes a toll on readers, both emotionally and intellectually. The constant farce that is Ludvig's existence only ever seems to get worse. He is unarguably responsible for this at several junctures, and what's worse is that he's always aware on some level of this. Ludvig is a massively detail-oriented character, and unfortunately, to himself, his life has been defined by the details he missed, not those that he observed and carefully attempted to twist to his liking. It is left to the reader to decide which is Ludvig's greatest tragedy; there are more than I care to share here, but suffice to say that by the end of the novel it would be difficult to make a full accounting for his misery.<br /><br />It bears mentioning that "The Joke" will likely upset people who are offended by reading about abuse directed toward women. Indeed, Kundera does not present us with a single solidly strong female character, and while Ludvig's realization that his own treatment of women (or just Lucie in particular) as objects has led to his misery (and is therefore presented in a negative light), there is little thereafter that addresses the issue directly. <br /><br />That said, I still highly recommend "The Joke" to anyone willing to put the time and effort into it. Definitely give this one a shot if you're able. </span>
