  <span id="freeText1646583475060386485" style="display:none">Long subjected to wasteful discussions of its political worth and relevance, "The Joke", re-read when one is a bit older and less prone to the exhausting insufferable manifestivaled gutterances of youth, "The Joke" is simply a wonderful novel about love, suffering, and our utter incapacity to redeem ourselves when it is most convenient.<br />Don't try to read to much into this or you're going to miss the point. Kundera was writing about people acting within the context of vast colossal institutions that didn't know how to behave very well on their own and that were even worse at trying to convince people how to act. We are driven by much more than blind obeisance to abstract, over-arching faiths, no matter what they are and this novel succeeds at reminding us of that in a way that is often hilarious, sad, and never without a wry warmth.<br /></span>
