  <span id="freeText9956626092679656191" style="display:none">I read it as part of a set of debut novels by novelists who later became major names in contemporary literature. This novel is written in Czech language and later translated into English as a group effort which included the novelist himself. I have been a fan of Kundera since I read his insightful expositions on the art of novel and on the nature of art in general. <br /><br />The rise and consolidation of Communist rule in 1950s Czechoslovakia forms the background of this novel. The protagonist, himself a budding Communist student, is expunged from the party and kicked out of the university to be sent to slave away in the mines run by the military. Why? He unwittingly made a joke, in a letter to his girlfriend, about the Communist politics and leaders. Her dedicated and mirthless girlfriend took it to be a sacrilege - a blasphemy of religious proportions - and reported it to the authorities. <br /><br />The story revolves around his attempts to come to terms with the turn of his fate as he languishes in a military camp in a battalian which is supposed to comprise of the most dangerous anti-state opposition figures. But he finds out that most dissenters had been put their for petty reasons: for not supporting wholeheartedly and enthusiastically one of the policies of the Communist government; and another is punished simply as a preemptive measure because of his father who's a oppositional activist. <br /><br />When he regains limited freedom after a few years of hard labour at the military camp, writing in hate for what his life has become, he launches himself on a campaign to take revenge on another of his friends who had him voted out of the university and the party and who in effect authored his subsequent travails. This is where I think the novel becomes thin. His personal philosophy suffers a painful realisation of some sort and makes him do something he wasn't planning.<br /><br />It's a good debut novel in that it goes beyond the usual noisy political sloganeering found in novels that deal with highly charged political subject matter, such as Orwell's 1984, and delves deeper into the mysteries of totalitarian political collective on a psychological level, but unlike anything resembling the oft-seen 'pop psychology' which caricatures the problem and which any average person can write about. Jokes - humour and sarcasm - contends Kundera, is the most mysteriously powerful of dissenting tools in the world, and any power - be it religious, political, moral, etc - which has taken upon itself to reform the whole world in earnest, is greatly threatened by it, and can't tolerate it.<br /><br />In the case of the hero of our novel, the Communist government elevated a pathetic half-serious joke to the same status as of dangerous anti-state activity when, at the military camp, the authorities assigned him to a battalion reserved for top level dissenters - and this for us is the real joke.</span>
